<author><name><![CDATA[whicker]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-02-11T20:08:29-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-02-11T20:08:29-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7474&amp;p=73870#p73870</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7474&amp;p=73870#p73870"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[SFC cartridges and low-profile EEPROM]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7474&amp;p=73870#p73870"><![CDATA[
There aren't going to be adapter boards with flash already soldered on.<br />Now's the time to learn, I guess. It isn't even that hard-- put a smaller tip in your iron, put down a ton of solder flux, tape the chip down, go over it again with flux, clean your soldering iron tip, put a big droplet of solder on it, drag it across the pins, feed more solder as you're going across if it runs out.<br /><br />It will "magically" work for the most part, but use solder braid to get rid of the three or so bridges between pins that do develop.<br /><br />No pinouts match the mask chips perfectly, hence the need for an adapter board.<br /><br />Anything that is 5 volts with enough address lines and an 8-bit data bus will work.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4151">whicker</a> — Fri Feb 11, 2011 8:08 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
